				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\omega}_{\mathrm{scat}}={\omega}_{\mathrm{p}}\pm {\omega}_{\mathrm{osc}}, $$\end{document}

where subscripts oscÂ denotes the lattice or molecule vibration, p denotes the incident photon (often referred to as the pump photon) and scatÂ denotes the scattered light [1]. The binary operator (Â±) is determined by energy conservation. When the energy of the scattered photon is lower than that of the incident photon (i.e. red shifted), the process is referred to as Stokes Raman scattering. Conversely, when the energy of the scattered photon is higher than that of the incident photon (i.e. blue shifted), the process is referred to as anti-Stokes Raman scattering. The Raman process must also conserve momentum, which is expressed in wave vector form as:2kâscat=kâpÂ±qâ,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
