Toma et al. [298] previously demonstrated selective excitation of a single Raman mode and its CARS imaging of CNT using ultra-fast SPP pulse nanofocusing using an Au tapered tip. In a more recent publication, seminal work by Tomita et al. [155] demonstrated simultaneous nanofocusing of ultra-fast SPP pulses at 440 and 800ânm, which were coupled with a common diffraction grating structure. Figure 8a i, illustrates the scheme. The Al-tapered tip had an apex radius of ââ35ânm. Selective CARS microscopy that combined an 800ânm (Ï) SPP pump pulse and a 440-nm (2Ï) SPP probe pulse was achieved. Figure 8a ii illustrates the energy level process of Ï- and 2Ï-CARS. The pump pulse achieves selective vibrational excitation by spectral focusing [299â302]. Raman shift intensities with this 2Ï-CARS scheme were reported to increase by as much as 4 compared with that of Ï-CARS for monolayer graphene. The selectivity of vibration band excitation and background noise suppression were confirmed on the CARS intensity probed by a 2Ï-SPP plasmon pulse for a monolayer graphene sample. Venezuela et al. [8] reported the Raman lines in graphene associated with both phonon-defect processes (such as the D line at ÎÎ½~\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \Delta \overset{\sim }{\nu } $$\end{document} ~â1350âcmâ1) and two-photon processes (such as the 2D line). The 2D-band intensity in graphene was reduced monotonously when the defect concentration was increased, contrary to the D-band. Tomita et al. [155] applied their multi-vibrational-mode 2Ï-CARS imaging method to a multi-walled CNT (MWCNT) at the D, G and 2D bands. This dual-wavelength nanofocusing technique could open new nanoscale micro-spectroscopy and optical excitation schemes in SPM, such as sum frequency mixing, two-photon excitation (Ï+2Ï) and pump-probe schemes.Fig. 8
a i Illustration of tip-enhanced dual-wavelength nanofocused CARS on a multi-walled carbon nanotube (MWCNT). a ii Energy diagram for Ï-CARS and 2Ï-CARS. When the difference frequency between pump and Stokes light matches the vibrational mode of the molecule, it is resonantly excited. When Ï and 2Ï-probe light is simultaneously incident within the dephasing time, Ï- and 2Ï-CARS photons are respectively generated. b i Simultaneous topographical 2Ï-CARS imaging of a MWCNT. b ii Composite image of three 2Ï-CARS images of the MWCNT using the 2Ï-CARS spectrum from D- (red), G- (blue) and 2D- (green) bands. Reprinted with permission from [155]
